        </figure>

        <h2>Crafting an Engaging Essay Introduction</h2>

        <p>The introduction sets the tone for your paper and should 
        make up about 10% to 15% of your total word count. To write 
        a strong essay introduction:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>The Hook:</strong> Start with a broad statement, 
          a relevant statistic, or a significant academic debate.</li>
          <li><strong>Context:</strong> Provide necessary background 
          information to help the reader understand the topic.</li>
          <li><strong>Signposting:</strong> Briefly mention the key 
          areas your essay will cover.</li>
          <li><strong>The Thesis Statement:</strong> Position this 
          clearly at the end of the introductory paragraph.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Writing Analytical Body Paragraphs</h2>

        <p>Each body paragraph must focus on a single main idea that 
        supports your thesis statement. Use the PEEL framework 
        (Point, Evidence, Explanation, Link) to keep your writing 
        structured.</p>

        <figure>
          <img
            src="/ThesisArcPro/images/peel-paragraph-framework-university-essay.webp"
            alt="A color-coded educational chart explaining the PEEL 
            writing method: Point, Evidence, Explanation, and Link, 
